<%# Docs chapter 04 — the ranking. Vote merging, the franchise checkpoint,
    the slider and discover mode. Copy rule: simple words, no hyphens in
    visible text. %>
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <%- include('../partials/head', { title: 'The ranking — how it works' }) %>
</head>
<body class="min-h-screen bg-paper font-sans text-ink antialiased">
  <%- include('../partials/frame') %>
  <%- include('../partials/nav') %>

  <main class="relative mx-auto max-w-6xl overflow-hidden px-6 py-12">
    <span class="pointer-events-none absolute -right-10 top-6 select-none font-serif text-[15rem] font-extrabold leading-none text-ink/[0.04]" aria-hidden="true">番</span>

    <div class="reveal relative">
      <%- include('../partials/docs-header') %>

      <div class="mt-10 max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink/85">
        <p>
          By this point the finders have returned their candidates and
          every signal has an opinion about each one. This chapter is the
          last stretch: how those opinions become one ranked list, what
          gets stopped at the gate on the way, and where you get to put
          your thumb on the scale.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-12">
        <span class="font-serif text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight">合算</span>
        <span class="jp-sub">gassan — adding up the votes</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-5 max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink/85">
        <p>
          Each signal speaks its own unit. The story signal returns an
          angle, the tag signal returns a sum of rarity weights, the genre
          signal returns an overlap fraction. Added raw, the loudest unit
          would drown the rest, so first each signal's scores are squeezed
          onto one shared scale, from zero for its weakest candidate to one
          for its strongest.
        </p>
        <p>
          Then every score is multiplied by its signal's weight and the
          results are added. There is no bonus rule for agreement, because
          none is needed: a show that three signals found simply collects
          three votes, and rises past a show that collected one. The nudges
          from chapter three adjust these sums, and the final order is the
          red thread.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-12">
        <span class="font-serif text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight">関所</span>
        <span class="jp-sub">sekisho — the checkpoint</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-5 max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink/85">
        <p>
          The most similar thing to any show is always its own sequel, and
          a list that says so is useless. So before the votes are counted,
          a checkpoint stands between the candidates and the ranking. The
          engine walks the relations graph outward from the show you are
          viewing, up to three steps, and everything that walk reaches,
          sequels, prequels, films, specials and recaps, is turned away.
        </p>
        <p>
          Why three steps and not "follow every link forever"? Because the
          relations data does not say <em>how</em> two shows are related,
          and crossover specials chain unrelated franchises together. Walk
          forever from some big franchises and you would reach thousands of
          titles and ban a tenth of the catalog. Three steps covers a real
          franchise, including its stragglers, without that damage.
        </p>
        <p>
          The graph alone is not enough, though. The catalog holds some
          entries twice under the same name, and the duplicate copy often
          carries no relation links at all, so it would stroll past the
          graph check. The checkpoint therefore also turns away any
          candidate whose title matches, or begins the same way as, a
          title in the franchise. And just before the list ships, one last
          sweep removes twins, so the same title never occupies two slots.
          None of this hides the franchise from you: it still appears on
          the page in its own relations section, which is where it belongs.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-12">
        <span class="font-serif text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight">調整</span>
        <span class="jp-sub">chousei — the slider, and showing the work</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-5 max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink/85">
        <p>
          The weights are not sacred, and on every anime page the biggest
          two are yours. The slider above the red thread mixes
          <em>story</em> against <em>tags</em>: drag it toward story and
          the fingerprint vote grows louder, drag it toward tags and the
          community labels take over. The whole ranking is recomputed for
          your mix on the spot, which is only possible because the math is
          fast enough to run fresh on every view.
        </p>
        <p>
          Every card also names the finders that brought it in, in the
          small print under the title. That label is a promise about the
          whole system: any recommendation here can explain itself, and a
          feature that cannot explain itself does not ship.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-12">
        <span class="font-serif text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight">出会い</span>
        <span class="jp-sub">deai — discover mode</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-5 max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink/85">
        <p>
          The discover page runs the same engine with a looser grip. It
          draws one random, genuinely good show as a seed, asks the engine
          for a wide thread of forty matches from an extra deep candidate
          pool, shuffles them, and deals you eighteen. The shuffle is the
          point: the safest dozen picks are not always the most
          interesting, and a small spin of the wheel surfaces matches you
          would not have scrolled to. One press of the reroll draws a new
          seed and a new hand.
        </p>
        <p>
          What waits beyond this is honest roadmap: a popularity pass that
          adds a quality floor and a gentle boost for great shows few
          people have seen, and once watch histories exist, a discover
          mode that knows to skip the sequels of shows you have already
          finished. Both are listed with their real status in chapter
          three.
        </p>
      </div>

      <%- include('../partials/docs-pager') %>
    </div>
  </main>

  <%- include('../partials/footer') %>
</body>
</html>
